did.abstract: Adam Herbert served as the seventeenth president of Indiana University from 2003-2007. In November 2005, he received a vote of "no confidence" from an unofficial faculty vote and decided, in January 2006, not to renew his contract after it expired in 2008. After a new president was selected, Herbert resigned on June 30, 2007. The collection consists of records, correspondence, and administrative files from Herbert's tenure as Indiana University president.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: Select files closed to researchers. These are indicated in the finding aid.
Advance notice required for access to collection.

bioghist.head: Biographical Note
bioghist.p: Born in Muskogee, Oklahoma, Adam Herbert served as the seventeenth president of Indiana University from August 1, 2003 to June 30, 2007. He earned a Bachelor of Arts degree in political science and a Master of Public Administration degree from the University of Southern California. He received his Doctor of Philosophy degree in urban affairs and public administration from the University of Pittsburgh.

Herbert came to IU from the University of North Florida, where he was Regents Professor and founding executive director of the Florida Center for Public Policy and Leadership. He served as president of that university from 1989 to 1998.

In his inaugural address, Herbert noted that "the opportunity before us is to shape and lay the stones that will serve as the foundation for expansions and additions, new spires and buttresses of this magnificent cathedral of learning." Herbert oversaw several new initiatives in teaching, research, and public engagement. Under his direction, the faculty instituted a general education curriculum, and brought more than $1.7 billion to Indiana in research grants and contracts. He oversaw the development of the Indiana Life Sciences Initiative, designed to establish IU as one of the nation's leading centers of life sciences research and Indiana as a leader in the life sciences industry.

Herbert also helped each of IU's eight campuses become more market smart and mission centered by launching the Mission Differentiation initiative and enhanced IU's relationships with Indiana's community colleges. He undertook the university's first major administrative restructuring in 30 years, expanded IU's physical infrastructure through the construction or renovation of more than 3,000,000 square feet of university facilities, and significantly strengthened the university's athletics programs. During his presidency, Adam Herbert placed emphasis on fund raising, particularly in the area of student financial aid. He also promoted diversity in IU's faculty, staff and student body, challenging each IU campus to develop concrete diversity goals.

In 2005, after Herbert failed to appoint a permanent replacement for the Indiana University Bloomington Chancellor despite two searches, discontent faculty organized a meeting. In a straw poll of the 125 faculty members in attendance, 103 voted "no confidence" in Herbert's leadership abilities. On January 13, 2006, Herbert sent a letter to the IU Board of Trustees announcing his wish not to "serve the university as president beyond the period of my current contract which ends July 2008."
Herbert's last day as President was June 30, 2007.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The collection is organized into five series: Administrative Files, Alpha Files, Chronological Files, Meeting Files, and Calendars.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: The collection is organized into five series: Administrative Files, Alpha Files, Chronological Files, Meeting Files, and Calendars.

The first series, Administrative Files, 1999-2007, consists of administrative materials related to the management and functioning of the University. Included are files on the various academic departments and schools, accreditation, athletics, international programs, student organizations, state relations, and the regional campuses.

The next series, Alpha Files, 2003-2007, contains copies of Herbert's outgoing presidential correspondence organized into alphabetical files and therein by year. It is comprised largely of correspondence with IU staff, faculty, and fellow administrators.
The Chronological Files series, 2003-2007, contains copies of Herbert's presidential correspondence arranged chronologically.

The Meeting Files series, 2006-2007, contains files on various meetings Herbert had during the 2006-2007 academic school year. The contents of the files range from a single sheet agenda to extensive background material.

The Calendar series, 2004-2007, is comprised of information about Herbert's daily and monthly schedule. There is a detailed, day-by-day calendar for Herbert's schedule for 2004 and 2005. Other files contain invitations with notations about whether or not Herbert attended the events.
Those files which are restricted are indicated in the folder list below, but are stored physically at the end of the collection.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Material
relatedmaterial.p: Additional records such as newsletters, annual reports, bulletins, and publications may be accessed in the Archives of Institutional Memory.
Archived web sites for this office may be included in Archive-It.
Related photographs may be available in the University Archives Photographs Database.
